\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 If I were to try to paint a picture of that night in Bethlehem, there is one thing I would be sure not to omit.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 I would paint the rifted sky, opened to release the mingled praise of angels. I would depict the shepherds, listening in their wonder.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 I would hang the wondrous star in its place in the sky\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 heaven\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s sign of hope to a broken world. The peaceful village, the lowly manger, the quiet cattle in their stalls\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 all these should have a place.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 But somewhere in the distance I would set the inn with its lighted windows, its gayety within, and its crowded space\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 a house with a closed door, a place with room for all except the family of an artisan who was to be trusted with the rearing of a King.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Through the centuries this has been a most tragic story. It has been the most tragic because it has represented the most widespread condition. It has been the saddest because it has been the least realized.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 On the old battlefield of Sempach, where in 1386 the Swiss won a notable victory over the Austrians, there stands a monument of recognition to Arnold von Winkelried, a Swiss peasant, who on the day of that battle gave his life as the price of victory for his country.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 The Austrians were massed together with presented spears\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93A living wall, a human wood.\u8221\'94 There was only one hope of breaking through the armed line and that was for some one to dash against the phalanx and make an opening\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 at the cost of his life. Suddenly there was a cry: \u8220\'93Make way for liberty,\u8221\'94 and Arnold von Winkelried rushed forward, gathering an armful of Austrian lances into his own breast, but opening a breach through which his comrades poured themselves against their foes.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 The Swiss marched to victory that day, but it was over the dead body of a man who loved them and their cause even unto death, a man who was moved by the love which lays down its life for its friends.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 There is another spot\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 a place unmarked by any monument\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 where earth\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s supremest hero yielded up His life to make way for the liberty of His people. He gathered the wrath and the sting of a great world\u8217\'92s sin into His own heart, and led the way where others dared not tread.}
